    • Method Detail

      • isEqual

        public final boolean isEqual(VALUE value1,
                             VALUE value2)
        This method determines if the two given objects are equal to each other in a way semantically defined by this implementation. An implementation must fulfill the contract of the method Object.equals(Object). This means it is:
        • reflexive: isEquals(x, x) == true, especially: isEquals(null, null) == true
        • symmetric: isEquals(x, y) == isEquals(y, x)
        • transitive: (isEquals(x, y) == isEquals(y, z) == true) implies isEquals(x, z)
        • consistent: multiple invocations of isEquals(x, y) will always return the same result if x and y are unchanged.
        • null-compatible: for all x != null: isEquals(x, null) == isEquals(null, x) == false
        Specified by:
        isEqual in interface EqualsChecker<VALUE>
        Parameters:
        value1 - is the first value.
        value2 - is the second value.
        Returns:
        true if both values are null or both are NOT null and equal to each other in the way defined by this EqualsChecker implementation, false otherwise.

      • isEqualNotNull

        protected abstract boolean isEqualNotNull(VALUE value1,
                                          VALUE value2)
        Called from isEqual(Object, Object) if objects are both NOT same and NOT null.
        Parameters:

        value2 - is the first value to check.
        Returns:
        true if the given values are considered as equal, false otherwise.
